1. An order has an amount in cents (between 0 and 1 000 000), a customer age (between 0 and 150), a payment method (text, max 32 bytes), and a customer name (text, max 64 bytes).
2. An order decision has an amount, a priority (text), and an audit reference (text).
3. Validate an order's amount: accept it with the amount when the amount is strictly positive and does not exceed a maximum loaded from "/tmp/order_intake/max_amount.txt" at startup; otherwise reject with a reason mentioning the amount.
4. Validate an order's customer age: accept it with the age when the customer is at least 18; otherwise reject with a reason mentioning the age.
5. Process an order end-to-end: chain the amount validation and then the age validation; on both successes, also require that the payment method exactly matches the value loaded from "/tmp/order_intake/allowed_method.txt" at startup. When everything passes, build the order decision with the validated amount, a priority of "high" if the amount is at least 100 000 cents otherwise "standard", and an audit reference combining the customer name, the amount, and the current Unix timestamp. When any check fails, propagate the failure reason as the rejection.
